    mechanism: "Your body has a hormone system (renin-angiotensin) that constricts blood vessels and tells your kidneys to hold onto salt and water — both of which raise blood pressure. ACE inhibitors and ARBs block different points in that system, relaxing vessels and easing the load on your heart and kidneys. Beyond just lowering the number, they also slow scarring of heart and kidney tissue over years, which is where the longevity edge over older BP drugs comes from.",
    evidenceSummary: "HOPE (2000), EUROPA (2003), and meta-analyses show ACEi reduce all-cause mortality, MI, and stroke in high-risk patients. ARBs (valsartan, telmisartan) similar efficacy with better tolerability. Blood pressure control alone explains much of the benefit, but pleiotropic effects (anti-fibrotic, possibly anti-aging) are documented in animal models. SPRINT (2015) showed intensive BP lowering (target <120) reduces all-cause mortality.",
