    one: "The mortality data on EVOO consumption is among the strongest for any 'food'.",
    plain: "Extra-virgin olive oil isn't just a healthy fat — it's one of the most evidence-graded foods on the planet, with mortality reduction in multiple large trials. The polyphenol content matters: cheap supermarket EVOO is far weaker than fresh, dark-bottle, recently-harvested oil. Replace your butter, margarine, and seed oils with high-polyphenol EVOO. This is closer to a 'longevity food' than almost anything else.",
    mechanism: "Real EVOO contains a specific group of compounds (oleocanthal, oleuropein, hydroxytyrosol) that act as natural anti-inflammatories — oleocanthal in particular hits the same enzyme that ibuprofen does, just much more gently. Combined with the heart-healthy monounsaturated fat, the polyphenols protect blood vessels, calm chronic inflammation, and seem to slow age-related cognitive decline. Heat, light, and time degrade the polyphenols, which is why freshness and storage matter as much as price.",
    evidenceSummary: "PREDIMED RCT showed Mediterranean diet supplemented with EVOO (or nuts) reduced major CV events 30% over 5 years vs low-fat diet. Nurses' Health + Health Professionals follow-up showed each ~7g/day increase in olive oil intake associated with 8-14% lower CV/all-cause mortality. Hydroxytyrosol has EFSA-approved health claim for LDL oxidation.",
