    one: "Useful for secondary prevention. Net benefit in primary prevention is now disputed.",
    plain: "If you've already had a heart attack or stroke, low-dose aspirin reduces the chance of another one and is usually worth the bleeding risk. If you haven't — and most people haven't — the modern evidence no longer supports taking it 'just in case.' The bleeding risk often eats the cardiovascular benefit. Don't start daily aspirin without a real reason.",
    mechanism: "Aspirin permanently disables one of the chemicals platelets use to clump together and form clots. Less clot formation means fewer heart attacks and clot-type strokes — but also more bleeding from the stomach and brain. For someone with established heart disease, the trade is favorable: fewer events outweigh the bleeding. For someone healthy, the math has flipped in recent large trials. The bleeding risk grows with age, but so does the cardiovascular risk — so it's an individual calculation.",
    evidenceSummary: "ASPREE (2018) tested low-dose aspirin in healthy adults ≥70. Found no mortality benefit, slight bleeding increase, surprising increase in cancer mortality on aspirin. ARRIVE and ASCEND showed similar marginal-or-negative net effects in moderate-risk populations. For SECONDARY prevention (post-MI, post-stroke), aspirin remains standard of care with clear net benefit. USPSTF 2022 walked back primary prevention recommendations.",
    endpoints: ["All-cause mortality", "MACE", "Cancer incidence/mortality", "Major hemorrhage"],
    humanDose: "75-100 mg/day enteric-coated for cardiovascular indications.",
    lastReviewed: "2026-05-05",
    verdict: "If you've had an event, take it as your cardiologist directs. If you haven't and you're otherwise low-risk, the modern evidence does not support taking it just for longevity.",
    todo: ["If your cardiologist already has you on it after a heart attack, stent, or stroke: keep taking it. Don't stop without checking with them.", "If you don't have established heart disease: don't start it 'for prevention' on your own. The 2018–2022 trials (ARRIVE, ASPREE, ASCEND) shifted the consensus.", "If you're considering it: discuss with your doctor based on personal cardiovascular risk score AND bleeding risk score. There are calculators they can use.", "If on it: take 75–100 mg enteric-coated daily, with food. Avoid alcohol and NSAIDs (extra GI bleeding).", "Stop 5–7 days before any surgery (per surgeon's instructions).", "Don't give to children or teens with viral illness — Reye's syndrome risk."],
    forYou: "People with established cardiovascular disease (post-MI, post-stroke, stents, established peripheral artery disease) under physician guidance.",
    notForYou: "Most healthy adults without prior cardiovascular events. Active GI ulcer or recent bleeding. Severe liver disease. Children with viral illness.",
    contras: ["Active bleeding", "Recent surgery", "Severe liver disease", "Children with viral infections (Reye's)"],
    sides: ["GI bleeding", "Hemorrhagic stroke (small absolute increase)", "Easy bruising"],
    studies: [{"title": "Effect of Aspirin on All-Cause Mortality in Healthy Elderly (ASPREE)", "authors": "McNeil et al.", "year": 2018, "journal": "NEJM", "design": "RCT", "n": 19114, "url": "https://www.nejm.org/doi/10.1056/NEJMoa1803955", "finding": "No reduction in CVD events; HR for all-cause mortality 1.14 (slightly worse on aspirin); increased major hemorrhage.", "limitations": "Healthy elderly cohort already low-risk."}, {"title": "Aspirin in patients with previous MI or stroke (ATT meta-analysis)", "authors": "Antithrombotic Trialists' Collaboration", "year": 2009, "journal": "Lancet", "design": "Meta-analysis", "n": 17000, "url": "https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(09)60503-1/fulltext", "finding": "Secondary prevention: ~20% reduction in serious vascular events. Primary prevention net benefit uncertain.", "limitations": "Pooled trials; heterogeneous populations."}],
