    ev: "A",
    cost: "$8-15/month for generic psyllium husk powder (Now Foods, Yerba Prima) or unflavored Metamucil. Sweetened/flavored versions slightly more.",
    tier: 2,
    tags: ["Cardiovascular", "Metabolic", "Gut health"],
    targets: ["cvd", "metabolic"],
    one: "Soluble fiber with FDA-recognized heart-disease risk reduction claim. Lowers LDL cholesterol and improves bowel function. Genuinely useful, often overlooked.",
    plain: "Soluble fiber (the kind that turns into gel in your gut, like the texture of cooked oatmeal). About 10g per day lowers your LDL cholesterol by ~9% — comparable to a low-dose statin. The FDA officially approves the heart-disease-prevention claim. Also fixes constipation and diarrhea (yes, both), and slightly smooths blood-sugar spikes after meals. Cheap, well-tolerated after the first couple weeks.",
    mechanism: "When you eat psyllium with water, it forms a thick gel in your gut. That gel grabs onto bile acids (which your liver makes from cholesterol) and carries them out of your body in stool. So your liver has to pull more cholesterol out of your blood to make new bile — lowering your LDL. The same gel also slows how fast sugar from your meal hits your bloodstream.",
    evidenceSummary: "Jovanovski 2018 meta-analysis (28 RCTs, n=1,924): psyllium 10.2 g/day reduced LDL by 0.23 mmol/L (~9%) and apoB by similar margin. FDA approved heart-disease risk reduction health claim in 1998 for ≥7g psyllium/day. Multiple meta-analyses (de Bock 2017; Brum 2018) confirm modest BP reduction and post-prandial glucose smoothing. Strong evidence for IBS-C and IBS-D (paradoxically helps both — fiber gel normalizes both ends of stool consistency). Generally well-tolerated; main caveat is gas/bloating during first 2 weeks.",
    endpoints: ["LDL cholesterol", "ApoB", "Post-prandial glucose", "Bowel function", "Blood pressure (modest)"],
    humanDose: "7-15 g psyllium husk per day, divided into 2-3 doses, taken with at least 250 mL water each.",
    lastReviewed: "2026-05-06",
    verdict: "Underrated. Cheap (Metamucil generic <$10/mo), well-tolerated after initial bloating, and has FDA-grade evidence for cardiovascular risk reduction. Equivalent LDL reduction to a low-dose statin. If you don't eat 25-35g daily fiber from food, psyllium is probably the highest-value supplement you can take. Take separately from medications.",
    todo: "Start with 5g (1 teaspoon) once daily mixed in 250 mL water, drunk immediately. Increase to 7-15g/day in divided doses (typically before meals). ALWAYS take with full glass of water. Take medications 2 hours before or after psyllium (it binds them). Expect 1-2 weeks of gas/bloating during gut adaptation. Generic Metamucil (sugar-free version) is cheapest; the orange-flavor sweetened version contains sugar/artificial sweetener.",
    forYou: ["Elevated LDL not yet on a statin", "On a statin but not at target", "Constipation or alternating bowel habits (IBS)", "Don't eat 25-35g fiber/day from food", "Type 2 diabetes — improves post-prandial glucose"],
    notForYou: ["Already eat ≥35g fiber/day from beans, oats, vegetables — diet wins", "Esophageal stricture or swallowing difficulty (choking risk)", "Have to take many medications throughout the day — timing becomes complex"],
    contras: ["Esophageal stricture or swallowing difficulty", "Bowel obstruction", "Take separately from medications (binds them — separate by 2 hours)"],
    sides: ["Gas, bloating in first 1-2 weeks (resolves)", "Esophageal obstruction if taken without enough water"],
    studies: [{"title": "Effect of psyllium (Plantago ovata) fiber on LDL cholesterol and alternative lipid targets, non-HDL cholesterol and apolipoprotein B: a systematic review and meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials", "authors": "Jovanovski E, Yashpal S, Komishon A, Zurbau A, Blanco Mejia S, Ho HVT, Li D, Sievenpiper J, Duvnjak L, Vuksan V", "year": 2018, "journal": "Am J Clin Nutr", "design": "Meta-analysis (28 RCTs)", "n": 1924, "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30239559/", "finding": "Psyllium (median 10.2 g/day) reduced LDL by 0.23 mmol/L, non-HDL by 0.30 mmol/L, apoB by 0.04 g/L vs control over median 7 weeks. Effect dose-dependent.", "limitations": "Most trials short-term. Heterogeneous baseline cholesterol levels."}, {"title": "Cholesterol-lowering effects of dietary fiber: a meta-analysis", "authors": "Brown L, Rosner B, Willett WW, Sacks FM", "year": 1999, "journal": "Am J Clin Nutr", "design": "Meta-analysis (67 trials, multiple fibers)", "n": null, "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9925120/", "finding": "Soluble fibers (oat β-glucan, psyllium, pectin, guar) lowered LDL ~5-10% in dose-dependent fashion. Psyllium effect ~equivalent to oat β-glucan per gram.", "limitations": "Older meta-analysis. Newer Jovanovski 2018 supersedes for psyllium specifically."}],
