    plain: "Acarbose is a cheap diabetes drug that slows how fast your gut absorbs starches and sugars from a meal — flattening the blood-sugar spike afterward. In mice it consistently extends lifespan. In humans the longevity case is plausible but not proven. The catch: it ferments undigested carbs in your gut, which causes a lot of gas. That side effect is why most people who could benefit don't take it.",
    mechanism: "After you eat a carb-heavy meal, an enzyme in your gut wall breaks starch into sugar so it can absorb into your blood. Acarbose blocks that enzyme. Result: less sugar absorbed quickly, smaller spike, gentler insulin response. The undigested carbs continue down to your colon where bacteria ferment them — producing gas (the side effect) and short-chain fatty acids that may themselves be beneficial for your gut lining and metabolism.",
    evidenceSummary: "ITP showed acarbose extends median male mouse lifespan 22% (largest single-agent effect in ITP for males). Female effect smaller. STOP-NIDDM trial showed acarbose reduced T2DM incidence and possibly cardiovascular events in pre-diabetics. Widely used in Asia for diabetes; underused in Western practice. GI side effects (gas, bloating) limit adoption.",
