    one: "Daily coffee (3-5 cups) is consistently associated with lower all-cause mortality across dozens of cohort studies. Causality probable but not proven.",
    plain: "Daily coffee (3-5 cups) is one of the most consistent food/beverage patterns associated with lower mortality in observational studies — about 17% lower all-cause death rate, with strong protective signals for type 2 diabetes, Parkinson's, liver disease, and several cancers. The evidence isn't from randomized trials but the signal is unusually consistent across populations and ages. Use filtered (drip) coffee — espresso/French press at high volumes raises cholesterol slightly.",
    mechanism: "Coffee is a complex mix, not just caffeine. The polyphenols (chlorogenic acid) are antioxidants, caffeine improves insulin sensitivity slightly, and the whole package reduces low-grade inflammation. The reasons it protects against Parkinson's and liver disease aren't fully understood — but the patterns hold across many countries and decades, which is unusual for nutrition research.",
    evidenceSummary: "Poole 2017 BMJ umbrella review (201 meta-analyses): 3-5 cups/day associated with 17% lower all-cause mortality (largest reduction at this dose), lower CVD mortality, and reduced T2D, liver disease, Parkinson's, and several cancers. UK Biobank analysis (n=171,616) confirmed J-shaped curve with optimal benefit at 2-3 cups/day. Key caveats: (1) all observational, (2) effect attenuated in slow caffeine metabolizers (CYP1A2*1F variant), (3) unfiltered coffee (espresso, French press) raises LDL via cafestol — drip/filter coffee preferred for lipids.",
