    tier: 2,
    tags: ["Cardiovascular", "Performance", "Blood pressure"],
    targets: ["cvd"],
    one: "Dietary nitrate from leafy greens and beetroot is converted to nitric oxide. Modest BP reduction and exercise-performance benefit. Whole-food approach beats supplements.",
    plain: "Nitrate from leafy greens (arugula, spinach, beets) is converted by bacteria in your mouth into nitric oxide — the same molecule that drugs like Viagra release. It mildly lowers blood pressure (about 4/1 mmHg) and improves exercise performance by about 3-5%. The effect is real but small. Important: mouthwash kills the bacteria that do the conversion, so harsh antiseptic mouthwash on cardio days literally undoes this.",
    mechanism: "Plants store nitrate (a salt) in their leaves. When you eat them, bacteria living on your tongue convert the nitrate to nitrite, then your body converts that to nitric oxide. Nitric oxide relaxes your blood vessels, lowers blood pressure, and seems to make your muscles use oxygen slightly more efficiently during exercise.",
    evidenceSummary: "Siervo 2013 meta-analysis (16 RCTs, n=254): inorganic nitrate or beetroot juice reduced systolic BP 4.4 mmHg, diastolic 1.1 mmHg in normotensive and hypertensive adults. Effect dose-dependent. Multiple smaller RCTs also show reduced O2 cost of submaximal exercise (~3-5%) and improved time-to-exhaustion. Long-term mortality data not yet available, but high vegetable intake (DASH-style) consistently associated with lower CV mortality in observational studies — likely mediated in part by nitrate.",
    endpoints: ["Systolic/diastolic BP", "Endothelial function (FMD)", "Exercise performance"],
    humanDose: "5-10 mmol nitrate/day (1-2 cups raw arugula/spinach, or 250-500 mL beetroot juice, or one large beet).",
    lastReviewed: "2026-05-06",
    verdict: "Eat 1-2 cups of leafy greens daily — that's the intervention. The actual benefit comes from real food, not supplements. If you hate vegetables, beetroot juice (250mL/day) is the most concentrated source studied. Avoid antiseptic mouthwash on training days — kills the oral bacteria you need. Effect is modest but free if you're already eating vegetables.",
    todo: "Eat 1-2 cups of nitrate-rich leafy greens (arugula, spinach, swiss chard, beet greens) daily. Or drink 250-500 mL beetroot juice (Beet It Sport Shot or equivalent). For exercise benefit: take 2-3 hours before training. Avoid antiseptic mouthwash (chlorhexidine, Listerine) on training days — it kills the oral bacteria that activate nitrate.",
    forYou: ["Borderline or stage-1 hypertension", "Endurance athlete looking for legal performance boost", "Anyone not eating vegetables — start here, biggest payoff per change"],
