    one: "Sleep regulator with broader antioxidant + mitochondrial effects. Lower doses better than commonly sold.",
    plain: "Melatonin isn't just a sleep aid — it's a master signal for your body's daily rhythm and a surprisingly potent antioxidant. Most over-the-counter doses (3–10 mg) are 10–30x higher than what works. Try 0.3–0.5 mg first; bigger doses can cause grogginess and aren't more effective. Cheap, generally safe, useful for jet lag and shift work.",
    mechanism: "Your brain's pineal gland releases melatonin when it gets dark, which is your body's signal that it's time to shift into sleep-and-repair mode. Production drops dramatically with age — older adults make a fraction of what teenagers do. Beyond sleep, melatonin also acts as a free-radical scavenger inside mitochondria, where most cellular damage happens. Many of the effects attributed to it require very small doses; megadosing may actually disrupt your natural rhythm.",
    evidenceSummary: "Strong evidence for sleep latency in jet lag and shift work; modest in primary insomnia. Higher doses (3-10mg) shown in some trials to reduce mortality risk in elderly cohorts and benefit COVID outcomes. Most US supplement doses (3-10mg) are 10-30x physiological; 0.3-0.5mg may be more appropriate for sleep.",
    endpoints: ["Sleep quality", "Mortality (small RCTs)", "Inflammatory markers"],
    humanDose: "0.3-10mg before bed. Lower doses (0.3-1mg) often as effective as higher.",
