    one: "Diabetes drug with intriguing longevity signal in observational data. TAME trial in progress.",
    plain: "Metformin is a cheap, decades-old diabetes drug that diabetics on it seem to live longer than even non-diabetics — which is strange and interesting. Whether healthy people benefit is genuinely unclear. The big trial (TAME) is still running. Important catch: it blunts the muscle and fitness gains you get from hard exercise, so if you train seriously, this is a real tradeoff.",
    mechanism: "Metformin tells your liver to dump less sugar into your blood, and makes your muscles and cells more sensitive to insulin. It also gently stresses cells in a way that triggers their cleanup and repair machinery — similar to what fasting or exercise does, but milder. The exercise-blunting effect comes from the same pathway: the cellular stress signal that normally tells your muscles to adapt and grow stronger gets dampened.",
    evidenceSummary: "In type 2 diabetes: foundational RCT evidence. UKPDS 34 (1998, n=753) — metformin reduced all-cause mortality 36% in newly-diagnosed overweight T2D over 10.7 years vs conventional treatment. 10-year UKPDS post-trial follow-up (2008) showed legacy effect: 27% mortality reduction persisted after glucose control converged. Bannister 2014 cohort (n=78,241) suggested diabetics on metformin had longer survival than matched non-diabetic controls — striking but observational. In non-diabetics: ITP mouse study showed no lifespan extension alone. MASTERS RCT (2019) found metformin BLUNTED cardiorespiratory fitness gains from exercise training in healthy older adults. TAME trial (Barzilai) aims to test whether metformin delays multimorbidity in non-diabetics — not read out yet. Cancer-prevention meta-analyses suggest modest reductions in colorectal/liver/pancreatic cancer in T2D, all observational. Bottom line: gold standard for T2D; the longevity-in-healthy-people pitch remains a hypothesis.",
    endpoints: ["All-cause mortality (T2DM cohorts)", "Insulin sensitivity", "Cancer incidence", "Cardiovascular events"],
    humanDose: "500-2000 mg/day extended-release with food. Diabetic dose; longevity dose unclear.",
    lastReviewed: "2026-05-06",
    verdict: "Type 2 diabetes: yes, first-line, the data is overwhelming. Non-diabetics for longevity: not yet — the only RCT data shows it BLUNTS exercise gains. If you exercise hard for fitness, metformin is a poor fit. Wait for TAME. If you're pre-diabetic and exercise is hard to maintain, the diabetes-prevention case is stronger.",
    todo: ["If you have type 2 diabetes or pre-diabetes — this is probably already on your doctor's table. Talk to them.", "If you're healthy and want it for longevity: ask about it explicitly. Most primary docs won't prescribe off-label; longevity-focused clinics will.", "Start at 500 mg extended-release with dinner to minimize GI upset. Many people work up to 1000–1500 mg/day over weeks.", "If you exercise hard for performance/muscle: take it on rest days only, or skip it on heavy training days. Or skip the drug entirely.", "Get a B12 level checked yearly — long-term metformin can quietly drop B12.", "Drink water. Stop if you're sick with vomiting/diarrhea (rare risk of lactic acidosis when dehydrated)."],
    forYou: "People with pre-diabetes, fatty liver, PCOS, or strong family history of type 2 diabetes who don't train at high intensity for performance gains.",
    notForYou: "Serious athletes or anyone whose primary goal is maximizing strength/hypertrophy from training. Also: kidney impairment, on contrast dye, or chronic alcohol use.",
    contras: ["eGFR <30", "Acute illness", "IV contrast (hold 48h)", "Heavy alcohol use"],
    sides: ["GI distress", "B12 deficiency (long-term)", "Lactic acidosis (rare)"],
    studies: [{"title": "Can metformin extend lifespan? Effects on chronologically aged mice (ITP)", "authors": "Strong et al.", "year": 2016, "journal": "Aging Cell", "design": "RCT (mice)", "n": 600, "url": "https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/acel.12446", "finding": "Metformin alone did NOT extend median lifespan in male mice. Combined with rapamycin showed modest benefit.", "limitations": "Mouse, male only, single dose."}, {"title": "Metformin use and mortality among patients with type 2 diabetes (UKPDS 34)", "authors": "Bannister et al.", "year": 2014, "journal": "Diabetes Obes Metab", "design": "Cohort", "n": 78241, "url": "https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/dom.12354", "finding": "Diabetics on metformin had longer survival than matched diabetics on sulfonylureas AND than matched non-diabetic controls (HR ~0.85).", "limitations": "Observational; selection bias possible."}, {"title": "Metformin inhibits mitochondrial adaptations to aerobic exercise training (MASTERS)", "authors": "Konopka et al.", "year": 2019, "journal": "Aging Cell", "design": "RCT (humans)", "n": 53, "url": "https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/acel.12880", "finding": "Metformin blunted improvements in cardiorespiratory fitness from exercise training in non-diabetic older adults.", "limitations": "Small N; surrogate endpoints."}, {"title": "Effect of intensive blood-glucose control with metformin on complications in overweight patients with type 2 diabetes (UKPDS 34)", "authors": "UK Prospective Diabetes Study (UKPDS) Group", "year": 1998, "journal": "Lancet", "design": "RCT", "n": 753, "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=Effect%20of%20intensive%20blood-glucose%20control%20with%20metformin%20on%20complications%20in%20overweight%20patients%20with%20type%202%20diabetes%20%28UKPDS%2034%29", "finding": "Metformin (vs conventional treatment) reduced any diabetes-related endpoint by 32%, all-cause mortality by 36%, and MI by 39% in newly-diagnosed overweight T2D patients over 10.7 years. Foundational RCT establishing metformin as first-line.", "limitations": "Modest sample for primary metformin arm; T2D-specific population, not generalizable to non-diabetics."}, {"title": "10-Year follow-up of intensive glucose control in type 2 diabetes (UKPDS post-trial)", "authors": "Holman et al.", "year": 2008, "journal": "NEJM", "design": "RCT extension follow-up", "n": 4209, "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18784090/", "finding": "Legacy effect — even after the RCT ended and glucose control converged between groups, the metformin group maintained reduced MI (33%) and mortality (27%) at 10-year follow-up.", "limitations": "Post-trial observational; potential for unmeasured confounders during follow-up."}, {"title": "Metformin and cancer: an existing drug for cancer prevention? (meta-analysis)", "authors": "Yu et al.", "year": 2019, "journal": "Annals of Translational Medicine", "design": "Meta-analysis", "n": 65540, "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=Metformin%20and%20cancer%3A%20an%20existing%20drug%20for%20cancer%20prevention%3F%20%28meta-analysis%29", "finding": "Metformin associated with reduced cancer incidence and mortality in T2D, especially colorectal, liver, and pancreatic. Effect size modest but consistent across studies.", "limitations": "All observational — confounding by indication is plausible (sicker patients on alternatives)."}],
