    tags: ["Periodontal", "Inflammation"],
    targets: ["cvd", "neurodegenerative-other", "cognitive-decline", "inflammaging"],
    one: "Periodontitis is independently associated with cardiovascular and Alzheimer's risk.",
    plain: "Gum disease is one of the most underrated drivers of long-term health damage. Chronically inflamed gums seed bacteria into your bloodstream that show up in heart-artery plaques and Alzheimer's brains. Floss every day, get cleanings twice a year, and treat gum disease aggressively if you have it. This is a longevity lever masquerading as a hygiene chore.",
    mechanism: "Your mouth has its own ecosystem of bacteria. When you don't disrupt it daily (with brushing and flossing), certain bad actors — especially Porphyromonas gingivalis — start to dominate. They cause your gums to inflame, bleed slightly, and become a leaky border. From there, the bacteria and the inflammatory chemicals leak into your bloodstream, where they contribute to artery plaque and have even been found inside Alzheimer's-affected brain tissue. Treating gum disease isn't just about teeth — it's about systemic inflammation.",
    evidenceSummary: "Multiple cohort studies show periodontitis associated with 25-50% increased CV mortality, increased Alzheimer's, increased pancreatic and oral cancers. RCTs of periodontal treatment show improvements in endothelial function and HbA1c. Direct mortality RCTs lacking, but mechanistic + cohort evidence consistent.",
    endpoints: ["CV mortality (cohort)", "Alzheimer's incidence", "Cancer incidence", "Endothelial function"],
    humanDose: "Daily flossing + brushing 2x/day; professional cleanings 2x/year; periodontal treatment if disease present.",
    lastReviewed: "2026-05-05",
    verdict: "Floss. Get cleanings. Treat gum disease aggressively. Underrated longevity lever masquerading as a hygiene chore.",
    todo: ["Brush twice a day for 2 full minutes. Electric toothbrush (Oral-B or Sonicare) is meaningfully better than manual.", "Floss every night. Not 'when food is stuck' — every night. Water flossers (Waterpik) work for those who hate string floss.", "Professional cleaning every 6 months. Every 3–4 months if you have any history of gum disease.", "If your dentist mentions 'pockets' or 'periodontitis': take it seriously. Get a deep cleaning (scaling and root planing). May need a periodontist.", "Notice bleeding gums when brushing or flossing? That's not normal. It means inflammation. Floss MORE, not less — should improve in 1–2 weeks. If it doesn't, see a dentist.", "Tongue scraping in the morning reduces bacterial load.", "Avoid antibacterial mouthwash daily — it disrupts the helpful oral microbiome too. Use only short-term if directed."],
