    plain: "A natural compound that helps your cells clean themselves up. People who eat lots of it (wheat germ, cheese, mushrooms) seem to live longer — but the study giving it as a pill for memory didn't show a benefit. Diet > pills here.",
    mechanism: "An autophagy switch — helps cells clean out their damaged parts. Animal studies show longer lifespan; the human evidence is much messier.",
    evidenceSummary: "The strongest human signal is a cohort association: in the BRUNECK prospective study (n=829, Italian alpine population), people in the highest tertile of dietary spermidine intake had ~5 years of additional life expectancy compared to the lowest, with a hazard ratio for mortality of 0.49 (Kiechl et al, AJCN 2018). Replication-ish in NHANES and Japanese cohorts. The Madeo group (Graz) has a strong mechanistic story tying this to autophagy, and small open-label trials suggested cognitive benefit. The pre-registered SmartAge RCT (Schwarz et al, JAMA Network Open 2022, n=100, 12 months wheat-germ-extract spermidine vs placebo in older adults with subjective cognitive decline) found NO significant effect on the primary memory endpoint (Mnemonic Similarity Task). Earlier smaller pilot RCTs (Wirth 2018) had reported a positive cognitive signal that did not replicate at scale. So: dietary association is real and consistent; supplementation as cognitive intervention has so far failed its best test. No mortality RCT exists.",
    endpoints: ["all-cause mortality (cohort only)", "memory performance (RCT, null)", "cardiac hypertrophy (animal)"],
    humanDose: "1.2 mg/day (SmartAge RCT, wheat germ extract). Some commercial products go higher. Dietary intake in BRUNECK ranged ~7-25 mg/day.",
    lastReviewed: "2026-05-07",
