    cost: "$10–25/mo",
    tier: 2,
    tags: ["Glycemic control", "Plant", "Diabetes"],
    targets: ["metabolic"],
    one: "Real RCT data for HbA1c reduction in T2D. Cheap, safe at typical doses. Modest effect compared to medications.",
    plain: "Fenugreek (Trigonella foenum-graecum) is a culinary spice and traditional medicine plant. Most studied for blood-sugar control: meta-analyses of RCTs in type 2 diabetes show roughly 0.5-0.9% HbA1c reduction with daily fenugreek seed powder (typically 5-10g/day). That's similar to what a low dose of metformin achieves. It's not as effective as standard medications and shouldn't replace them, but for prediabetes or as adjunct to medication it has the strongest plant-supplement evidence for glycemic control after berberine. The effect is mostly from soluble fibre and 4-hydroxyisoleucine, an unusual amino acid.",
    mechanism: "Fenugreek seeds are about 25% soluble fibre, which slows glucose absorption from the gut. They also contain a rare amino acid (4-hydroxyisoleucine) that increases insulin secretion in response to glucose — basically priming the pancreas to respond more vigorously when blood sugar rises. Combined, these effects modestly lower fasting glucose and the post-meal glucose spike.",
    evidenceSummary: "Neelakantan 2014 (Nutrition Journal) meta-analysed 10 RCTs of fenugreek in glycemic control (n=465 across T2D, prediabetes, healthy volunteers). Pooled effect: ~0.85% HbA1c reduction in T2D over 8-12 weeks, ~17 mg/dL fasting glucose reduction. Gupta 2001 (J Assoc Physicians India) RCT in 25 newly diagnosed T2D: 1g hydroalcoholic fenugreek seed extract daily for 2 months reduced fasting glucose 15% and HbA1c 0.7%. Lu 2008 (Asia Pac J Clin Nutr) RCT in 69 T2D: 10g fenugreek seed powder daily for 3 months reduced HbA1c 1.3% (largest effect in the literature; smaller subsequent trials show 0.5-0.9%). Sharma 1996 (older trial) in IDDM showed 25g daily reduced 24h glucose AUC and improved insulin response. Limitations: most trials are small, short, conducted in India/South Asia (different baseline diets, possible heterogeneity), and use varying preparations (seed powder, defatted seed, hydroalcoholic extract). The effect is robust across studies but smaller and less certain than for berberine. No long-term outcome trials (mortality, CV events).",
    endpoints: "HbA1c, fasting glucose, lipids (Neelakantan 2014; Lu 2008; Gupta 2001). No mortality or CV outcome trials.",
    humanDose: "5-10g fenugreek seed powder daily (most consistent dose); 1g hydroalcoholic extract daily (Gupta 2001)",
    lastReviewed: "2026-05-06",
    verdict: "Real glycemic effect. Cheap, well-tolerated at typical doses. Modest compared to medications — about 0.5-0.9% HbA1c reduction. Reasonable for prediabetes or as cheap adjunct to metformin in early T2D. Not a substitute for medical management of established diabetes. Skip the testosterone-marketed extract products; use seed powder.",
    todo: "5-10g fenugreek seed powder daily, with meals. Can be added to food (it's used in Indian cuisine — methi). Available as capsules; check the label for actual seed powder vs extract (extracts vary in 4-hydroxyisoleucine content). Avoid the fenugreek extract products marketed for testosterone — those are different formulations with weaker T2D evidence and stronger marketing claims. For glycemic effect, the simple seed powder is most studied.",
    forYou: "Adults with prediabetes or early T2D wanting an adjunct to lifestyle. People already on metformin who want additional small effect. Anyone with elevated HbA1c (5.7-7%) for whom medication isn't yet warranted.",
    notForYou: "Pregnancy (uterine stimulant traditionally used to induce labour; avoid). People with allergies to legumes/peanuts (fenugreek is botanically a legume; cross-reactivity reported). On warfarin or other anticoagulants (mild antiplatelet effect, theoretical interaction). T2D on insulin (additive hypoglycemia risk; coordinate with prescriber).",
    contras: "Pregnancy (uterine effects). Legume/peanut allergy (cross-reactivity). On insulin or sulfonylureas without prescriber awareness (additive hypoglycemia). On anticoagulants (theoretical antiplatelet interaction).",
    sides: "GI: bloating, gas, diarrhea (from soluble fibre, dose-dependent). Maple-syrup body odour (sotolon excretion). Mild hypoglycemia symptoms if combined with diabetes medications.",
    studies: [{"title": "Effect of fenugreek (Trigonella foenum-graecum L.) intake on glycemia: meta-analysis of clinical trials (Neelakantan 2014)", "authors": "Neelakantan et al.", "year": 2014, "journal": "Nutrition Journal", "design": "Meta-analysis of 10 RCTs", "n": 465, "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=Effect%20of%20fenugreek%20%28Trigonella%20foenum-graecum%20L.%29%20intake%20on%20glycemia%3A%20meta-analysis%20of%20clinical%20trials%20%28Neelakantan%202014%29", "finding": "Fenugreek significantly reduced fasting glucose (mean -0.96 mmol/L), 2h post-load glucose (-2.19 mmol/L), and HbA1c (-0.85%) in patients with diabetes.", "limitations": "Heterogeneous interventions (seed powder, extract, defatted); small individual trials; mostly Indian populations; surrogate endpoints only."}, {"title": "Beneficial effects of soluble dietary fiber from fenugreek seeds in patients with type 2 diabetes (Lu 2008)", "authors": "Lu et al.", "year": 2008, "journal": "Asia Pacific Journal of Clinical Nutrition", "design": "RCT, 12 weeks", "n": 69, "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=Beneficial%20effects%20of%20soluble%20dietary%20fiber%20from%20fenugreek%20seeds%20in%20patients%20with%20type%202%20diabetes%20%28Lu%202008%29", "finding": "10g fenugreek seed powder daily reduced HbA1c by 1.3% and triglycerides by 27% in T2D patients over 12 weeks.", "limitations": "Single trial; effect larger than meta-analysis pooled estimate; possible publication bias."}, {"title": "Effect of Trigonella foenum-graecum on blood lipids, blood sugar and platelet aggregation in patients with coronary artery disease (Bordia 1997)", "authors": "Bordia et al.", "year": 1997, "journal": "Prostaglandins, Leukotrienes and Essential Fatty Acids", "design": "RCT", "n": 60, "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=Effect%20of%20Trigonella%20foenum-graecum%20on%20blood%20lipids%2C%20blood%20sugar%20and%20platelet%20aggregation%20in%20patients%20with%20coronary%20artery%20disease%20%28Bordia%201997%29", "finding": "2.5g twice daily reduced total cholesterol and triglycerides; modestly reduced platelet aggregation.", "limitations": "Small; older methodology; secondary lipid endpoints."}, {"title": "Effect of hydroalcoholic extract of seeds of Trigonella foenum-graecum in newly diagnosed patients with type 2 diabetes mellitus (Gupta 2001)", "authors": "Gupta et al.", "year": 2001, "journal": "Journal of Association of Physicians India", "design": "RCT, 2 months", "n": 25, "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=Effect%20of%20hydroalcoholic%20extract%20of%20seeds%20of%20Trigonella%20foenum-graecum%20in%20newly%20diagnosed%20patients%20with%20type%202%20diabetes%20mellitus%20%28Gupta%202001%29", "finding": "1g/day hydroalcoholic fenugreek extract reduced fasting glucose 15% and HbA1c 0.7% vs control over 2 months.", "limitations": "Small; short; surrogate endpoints; extract preparation."}],
