    one: "Modest effects on cardiovascular and inflammatory markers; subjective wellbeing real.",
    plain: "Meditation is real but only if you actually do it — daily, for years. The 'I tried it for a week' dose isn't enough. Sustained practice reliably lowers stress hormones, blood pressure, and inflammation markers, and is associated with slower cellular aging. Free, scalable, no downside (for most people). The hard part is showing up daily.",
    mechanism: "Chronic stress keeps your nervous system stuck in fight-or-flight mode: cortisol elevated, blood pressure up, inflammation simmering. Meditation trains the part of the brain that turns the stress response down. Long-term meditators have measurable structural brain differences, slower aging of their telomeres (the protective caps on chromosomes), and lower inflammatory markers. None of this happens from a few sessions; it's a years-long practice that compounds.",
    evidenceSummary: "Schneider et al. (TM long-term cohort, 2012) showed reduced all-cause mortality (~25%) and CV mortality in TM practitioners vs controls. Goyal meta-analysis (JAMA Intern Med 2014) found moderate evidence for anxiety, depression, pain reduction; weak evidence on substance use, mood, sleep. BP-reducing effect modest (~3-5 mmHg). Effects highly dose-dependent (regular practice over years vs occasional).",
    endpoints: ["BP", "CV events (small RCT)", "Inflammation", "Telomere length", "Subjective wellbeing"],
    humanDose: "10-30 min/day, daily, sustained over months/years.",
    lastReviewed: "2026-05-05",
    verdict: "Real if you actually practice. The 'I tried it for a week' dose isn't enough. Daily 10-20 min for years gets the meaningful effects. Free, scalable, low downside.",
    todo: ["Start with 10 minutes a day. Same time, same place. Boring is fine — boring works.", "Use a guided app for the first 1–3 months: Waking Up (Sam Harris), Headspace, or Insight Timer. Calm is more sleep-focused.", "Don't try to 'stop your thoughts.' Just notice them and return to your anchor (breath, sound, body sensation).", "Build to 20–30 min/day over 6–12 months. The benefits scale with cumulative practice.", "Try a 1-day silent retreat after 6 months of daily practice. A multi-day retreat after a year. These compress months of progress into days.", "If meditation triggers severe anxiety, dissociation, or worsens trauma symptoms, stop and seek a trauma-informed teacher.", "Walking meditation, tai chi, and mindful yoga are valid alternatives if seated meditation doesn't fit you."],
    forYou: "Anyone with chronic stress, hypertension (low-end help), insomnia, anxiety, or who simply wants to age better. Especially valuable in midlife and beyond.",
    notForYou: "Active psychosis or severe untreated PTSD without professional support. Don't dive into deep practice during acute crisis.",
    contras: ["Active psychosis (precaution)"],
    sides: ["Rare: meditation-induced anxiety/dissociation in vulnerable individuals"],
    studies: [{"title": "Stress reduction in the secondary prevention of CVD (Schneider et al.)", "authors": "Schneider et al.", "year": 2012, "journal": "Circulation: Cardiovascular Quality and Outcomes", "design": "RCT", "n": 201, "url": "https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/CIRCOUTCOMES.112.967406", "finding": "TM reduced major CV events 48% over 5 years in CAD patients vs control health education.", "limitations": "Specific population; small N."}, {"title": "Meditation programs for psychological stress and well-being (Goyal et al.)", "authors": "Goyal et al.", "year": 2014, "journal": "JAMA Internal Medicine", "design": "Meta-analysis", "n": 3515, "url": "https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamainternalmedicine/fullarticle/1809754", "finding": "Moderate evidence for improved anxiety, depression, pain. Effects small to moderate.", "limitations": "Heterogeneous practices."}],
