    plain: "NR is the older sibling of NMN — same general goal of raising NAD+, slightly different pathway, and slightly more human research published. If you're going to bet on NAD+ restoration, NR has marginally better evidence. Same caveat: it raises the level, but whether that adds years to life is unproven.",
    mechanism: "Like NMN, NR is converted by your cells into NAD+, the maintenance coenzyme that drops with age. It uses a slightly different conversion pathway (NR → NMN → NAD+) so the end result is the same: more NAD+ in your tissues. NR has been on the market longer, has more peer-reviewed human studies, and has FDA Generally Recognized as Safe (GRAS) status as Niagen.",
    evidenceSummary: "More human RCTs than NMN, including dose-finding and small Phase 2 studies in mitochondrial disease, Parkinson's, and heart failure. Reliably raises NAD+. Functional outcomes mixed. Did not improve insulin sensitivity in obese men in one notable RCT. Better regulatory status than NMN in US (Niagen has GRAS status).",
