    one: "Compressed eating window. Modest metabolic benefit; mortality data thin.",
    plain: "Eating in an 8–10 hour window each day (skip breakfast OR skip dinner) gives modest metabolic benefits and many people find it useful as a discipline structure. It's not magic — total calorie quality and quantity still dominate. There's a slight signal that eating earlier in the day is metabolically better than eating later.",
    mechanism: "Your body has a daily rhythm — insulin sensitivity, digestion, hormone production all peak at certain times. Eating in a compressed window aligns intake with that rhythm and gives you a long nightly fasting state, when cells switch from growth mode to cleanup-and-repair. The simpler effect: fewer hours of eating means fewer total calories for most people, without needing willpower.",
    evidenceSummary: "TREAT trial (Lowe et al. 2020) showed 16:8 produced minimal weight loss vs 3 meals/day if calorie-matched, raising the question of whether calorie restriction (not timing) is doing the work. Other RCTs show modest improvements in glucose, BP, lipids when window is tight (8h or less). Whether timing OR calorie reduction is the active ingredient is debated. NHANES data suggest 16:8 may correlate with HIGHER CV mortality (debated).",
