    one: "Methyl donor often paired with NMN/NR to support methylation balance.",
    plain: "TMG (trimethylglycine, also called betaine) is a methyl-donor compound often paired with NMN or NR. The logic: NAD+ precursors burn through your body's methyl groups, and TMG replaces them. Reasonable to take if you're stacking NAD+ precursors; not magical alone. Naturally found in beets and spinach.",
    mechanism: "Your body uses 'methyl groups' as tags to switch genes on or off and to convert various molecules. NMN and NR — when broken down — consume methyl groups. If you're taking high doses of NAD+ precursors daily, you may slowly deplete your methyl pool, which can raise homocysteine (a cardiovascular risk marker). TMG donates methyl groups directly, refilling the pool. If you're not stacking NAD+ precursors, the case for TMG is weaker.",
    evidenceSummary: "Reliably lowers homocysteine in most populations. Lipids may shift unfavorably (LDL up) at higher doses. Endpoint trials on hard outcomes are limited; the homocysteine-CV link itself is now considered weak (per HOPE-2, VISP).",
