    mechanism: "NAD+ is a coenzyme your cells use for energy production, DNA repair, and many maintenance tasks. Levels drop substantially as you age — by middle age you have maybe half what you had at 20. The theory is that restoring NAD+ to youthful levels helps cells work better. NMN is one of the building blocks; you swallow it, your body converts it to NAD+. The level rise is documented. The downstream lifespan benefit is hoped for, not proven.",
    evidenceSummary: "Multiple human RCTs show NMN reliably raises blood NAD+ levels at 250-1000mg/day. Functional outcomes in humans are mixed: some show improvement in walking distance, insulin sensitivity, or muscle markers, others are negative. No long-term mortality or healthspan RCTs. Mouse studies show metabolic benefit but inconsistent lifespan extension. FDA classified NMN as a drug investigational article (2022), partially restricting US supplement sale.",
