    plain: "Vitamin K2 (different from the K1 in spinach) helps direct calcium to your bones instead of letting it deposit in your arteries — at least that's the theory. Cohort data looks good, but the gold-standard randomized trials are weak. Cheap hedge if you're already supplementing vitamin D. Don't take it if you're on a blood thinner like warfarin — it interferes with the medication.",
    mechanism: "Your body has two proteins that need vitamin K2 to do their job: one in your bones (helps deposit calcium where it belongs) and one in your arteries (actively prevents calcium from depositing where it doesn't). Without enough K2, you can have the strange combination of weak bones AND calcified arteries — calcium going to the wrong places. Eating fermented foods like natto, hard aged cheese, and egg yolks gives you K2; most modern diets don't have much.",
