    plain: "Quercetin is the famous flavonoid in apples, onions, and capers. As a senolytic, it only works combined with a chemo drug called dasatinib (D+Q protocol used in research). Solo quercetin pills are unimpressive. The food-source benefit is real — eat apples, onions, kale. The pill: skip.",
    mechanism: "Senolytics are drugs that selectively kill 'zombie' senescent cells — old damaged cells that won't die and leak inflammation. The most studied senolytic protocol is Dasatinib + Quercetin (D+Q). Critically: in the experiments, neither alone works well; the combination does. Without dasatinib, quercetin is just another flavonoid with mild antioxidant effects. The apple-and-onion food matrix has its own benefits, but those don't transfer cleanly to capsules.",
    evidenceSummary: "Alone, quercetin has modest effects on BP, allergic symptoms, and inflammation. The 'D+Q' senolytic protocol (dasatinib 100mg + quercetin 1000mg) has small open-label data in IPF, diabetic kidney disease, and Alzheimer's. As monotherapy, no significant longevity signal. Bioavailability poor; phytosome formulations help.",
