    one: "Famous red-wine polyphenol. Hype outpaced evidence.",
    plain: "Resveratrol is the famous red-wine compound that started the modern longevity-supplement industry. After 20 years of research, the evidence in humans is genuinely disappointing. The original sirtuin-activation story turned out to be a lab artifact. The bioavailability is terrible. Skip it. If you want polyphenols, eat berries, dark chocolate, EVOO, and drink green tea.",
    mechanism: "When researchers proposed in the 2000s that resveratrol activates 'longevity genes' (sirtuins), the supplement industry took off. Subsequent careful work showed the lab assay was misleading: resveratrol doesn't actually activate sirtuins directly in physiological conditions. It does have some antioxidant and AMPK-modulating effects, but the bioavailability is so poor that meaningful blood levels are hard to achieve. Multiple human trials have shown disappointingly small or zero effects on the markers of aging. The hype outpaced the data, and the data has not caught up.",
    evidenceSummary: "Sinclair lab's 2003 Nature paper launched the field. Subsequent RCTs in humans largely showed no significant longevity-relevant outcomes; some metabolic benefit in T2DM. ITP showed NO mouse lifespan extension at any tested dose. The SIRT1 mechanism was largely retracted/revised. Bioavailability remains a barrier (sub-1% in most preparations).",
