    one: "Stereoisomer of estradiol that extends male mouse lifespan without feminization. No human data.",
    plain: "17α-estradiol is a chemical mirror-image of the female hormone estradiol that, in mice, dramatically extends male lifespan without any feminizing effects. It's one of the most exciting findings from the NIA Interventions Testing Program. The catch: zero human trials. Don't take this. Watch the science.",
    mechanism: "Regular estradiol (estrogen) feminizes male tissues and isn't a longevity option. But its mirror-image molecule activates only a narrow subset of receptors — specifically ones in the liver and metabolism that improve insulin sensitivity and dial down growth signaling — without triggering the classic estrogen response. In male mice it extends median lifespan ~19% started in middle age. Whether the same molecule does anything good in human males is genuinely unknown.",
    evidenceSummary: "ITP showed 17α-estradiol extends median male mouse lifespan ~19%, replicated. No effect in females. Mechanism appears tissue-specific, with metabolic improvement (insulin sensitivity, body composition) without feminizing effects. NO human trials. Pharmacokinetics in humans not characterized for longevity dosing. Compounded versions exist but quality and safety are unstudied.",
