    one: "Senolytic flavonoid; clears senescent cells in mice. Human trials underway.",
    plain: "Fisetin is a plant compound (found in strawberries, in trace amounts) that selectively kills off 'zombie' senescent cells in mice — old damaged cells that hang around secreting inflammation. The Mayo Clinic is running human trials right now. It's the most credible 'longevity supplement' with a real mechanism, and the protocol is unusual: high doses for 2 days a month, not daily.",
    mechanism: "As you age, some of your cells stop dividing but refuse to die. They sit there leaking inflammatory chemicals that age the tissue around them. Senolytics are drugs that find these zombie cells and trigger their self-destruct sequence, leaving healthy cells alone. In mice, periodic senolytic treatment delays many age-related diseases. Fisetin is the cleanest natural-product senolytic identified so far. The 'two-day pulse' protocol mimics how it was used in the mouse studies.",
    evidenceSummary: "Yousefzadeh et al. (2018) screened 10 flavonoids for senolytic activity; fisetin was most potent. Late-life dosing extended median mouse lifespan ~10%. Human trials at Mayo Clinic (frailty, COVID, kidney disease) ongoing; preliminary signals on inflammation markers. Typical 'hit-and-run' protocol: 20mg/kg/day for 2 days, monthly. Bioavailability low; absorption window debated.",
    endpoints: ["Senescent cell markers", "Frailty", "Mouse lifespan", "Inflammation markers"],
